# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: time-series-econometrics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The ARCH model is appropriate when the error variance in a time series follows an autoregressive (AR) model; if an autoregressive moving average (ARMA) model is assumed for the error variance, the model is a **generalized autoregressive conditional heteroskedasticity** (**GARCH**) model.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] ARCH models are commonly employed in modeling financial time series that exhibit time-varying volatility and volatility clustering, i.e. periods of swings interspersed with periods of relative calm (this is, when the time series exhibits heteroskedasticity).
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] ARCH-type models are sometimes considered to be in the family of stochastic volatility models, although this is strictly incorrect since at time *t* the volatility is completely predetermined (deterministic) given previous values.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] To model a time series using an ARCH process, let $~\epsilon _{t}~$ denote the error terms (return residuals, with respect to a mean process), i.e. the series terms.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The random variable $z_{t}$ is a strong white noise process.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] An ARCH(*q*) model can be estimated using ordinary least squares.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] A method for testing whether the residuals $\epsilon _{t}$ exhibit time-varying heteroskedasticity using the Lagrange multiplier test was proposed by Engle (1982).
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Obtain the squares of the error ${\hat {\epsilon }}^{2}$ and regress them on a constant and *q* lagged values: ${\hat {\epsilon }}_{t}^{2}=\alpha _{0}+\sum _{i=1}^{q}\alpha _{i}{\hat {\epsilon }}_{t-i}^{2}$ where *q* is the length of ARCH lags.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The null hypothesis is that, in the absence of ARCH components, we have $\alpha _{i}=0$ for all $i=1,\cdots ,q$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The alternative hypothesis is that, in the presence of ARCH components, at least one of the estimated $\alpha _{i}$ coefficients must be significant.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] In a sample of *T* residuals under the null hypothesis of no ARCH errors, the test statistic *T'R²* follows $\chi ^{2}$ distribution with *q* degrees of freedom, where $T'$ is the number of equations in the model which fits the residuals vs the lags (i.e. $T'=T-q$ ).
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] If *T'R²* is greater than the Chi-square table value, we *reject* the null hypothesis and conclude there is an ARCH effect in the ARMA model.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] If *T'R²* is smaller than the Chi-square table value, we do not reject the null hypothesis.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] If an autoregressive moving average (ARMA) model is assumed for the error variance, the model is a generalized autoregressive conditional heteroskedasticity (GARCH) model.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Generally, when testing for heteroskedasticity in econometric models, the best test is the White test.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] However, when dealing with time series data, this means to test for ARCH and GARCH errors.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Exponentially weighted moving average (EWMA) is an alternative model in a separate class of exponential smoothing models.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] As an alternative to GARCH modelling it has some attractive properties such as a greater weight upon more recent observations, but also drawbacks such as an arbitrary decay factor that introduces subjectivity into the estimation.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The asymptotic, that is for large samples, standard deviation of $\rho (i)$ is $1/{\sqrt {T}}$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Individual values that are larger than this indicate GARCH errors.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] To estimate the total number of lags, use the Ljung–Box test until the value of these are less than, say, 10% significant.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The Ljung–Box Q-statistic follows $\chi ^{2}$ distribution with *n* degrees of freedom if the squared residuals $\epsilon _{t}^{2}$ are uncorrelated.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] It is recommended to consider up to T/4 values of *n*.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The null hypothesis states that there are no ARCH or GARCH errors.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Rejecting the null thus means that such errors exist in the conditional variance.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] , which ensures the non-negativity and stationarity of the variance process.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] For stock returns, parameter $~\theta$ is usually estimated to be positive; in this case, it reflects a phenomenon commonly referred to as the "leverage effect", signifying that negative returns increase future volatility by a larger amount than positive returns of the same magnitude.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] This model should not be confused with the NARCH model, together with the NGARCH extension, introduced by Higgins and Bera in 1992.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Integrated Generalized Autoregressive Conditional heteroskedasticity (IGARCH) is a restricted version of the GARCH model, where the persistent parameters sum up to one, and imports a unit root in the GARCH process.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The exponential generalized autoregressive conditional heteroskedastic (EGARCH) model by Nelson & Cao (1991) is another form of the GARCH model.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] where $g(Z_{t})=\theta Z_{t}+\lambda (|Z_{t}|-E(|Z_{t}|))$ , $\sigma _{t}^{2}$ is the conditional variance, $\omega$ , $\beta$ , $\alpha$ , $\theta$ and $\lambda$ are coefficients. $Z_{t}$ may be a standard normal variable or come from a generalized error distribution.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The formulation for $g(Z_{t})$ allows the sign and the magnitude of $Z_{t}$ to have separate effects on the volatility.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] This is particularly useful in an asset pricing context.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Since $\log \sigma _{t}^{2}$ may be negative, there are no sign restrictions for the parameters.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The GARCH-in-mean (GARCH-M) model adds a heteroskedasticity term into the mean equation.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The Quadratic GARCH (QGARCH) model by Sentana (1995) is used to model asymmetric effects of positive and negative shocks.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Similar to QGARCH, the Glosten-Jagannathan-Runkle GARCH (GJR-GARCH) model by Glosten, Jagannathan and Runkle (1993) also models asymmetry in the ARCH process.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The Threshold GARCH (TGARCH) model by Zakoian (1994) is similar to GJR GARCH.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Hentschel's **fGARCH** model, also known as **Family GARCH**, is an omnibus model that nests a variety of other popular symmetric and asymmetric GARCH models including APARCH, GJR, AVGARCH, NGARCH, etc.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] In 2004, Claudia Klüppelberg, Alexander Lindner and Ross Maller proposed a continuous-time generalization of the discrete-time GARCH(1,1) process.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] is the purely discontinuous part of the quadratic variation process of L .
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] where the positive parameters $\beta$ , $\eta$ and $\varphi$ are determined by $\alpha _{0}$ , $\alpha _{1}$ and $\beta _{1}$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Now given some initial condition $(G_{0},\sigma _{0}^{2})$ , the system above has a pathwise unique solution $(G_{t},\sigma _{t}^{2})_{t\geq 0}$ which is then called the continuous-time GARCH (**COGARCH**) model.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The multiplicative factor multi-frequency GARCH (MF2-GARCH) was proposed by Conrad and Engle (2025), and it features stationary returns and allows for recursive long-term volatility forecasts.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] They exploit the fact that daily standardized volatility forecast errors of one-component GARCH models are essentially unpredictable based on past daily standardized forecast errors, but a rolling window moving average of past daily standardized forecast errors does have predictive power.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Empirically, the long-term volatility component is closely linked to news about macroeconomics and monetary policy.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The immediate reaction of stock market indices to U.S. macroeconomic announcements (e.g., initial jobless claims or incoming orders) depends on the level of long-term stock market volatility.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The ZD-GARCH model does not require $~\alpha _{1}+~\beta _{1}=1$ , and hence it nests the Exponentially weighted moving average (EWMA) model in "RiskMetrics".
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Since $~\omega =0$ , the ZD-GARCH model is always non-stationary, and its statistical inference methods are quite different from those for the classical GARCH model.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Based on the historical data, the parameters $~\alpha _{1}$ and $~\beta _{1}$ can be estimated by the generalized QMLE method.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Spatial GARCH processes by Otto, Schmid and Garthoff (2018) are considered as the spatial equivalent to the temporal generalized autoregressive conditional heteroscedasticity (GARCH) models.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] In contrast to the temporal ARCH model, in which the distribution is known given the full information set for the prior periods, the distribution is not straightforward in the spatial and spatiotemporal setting due to the contemporaneous dependence between neighboring spatial locations.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] where $~s_{i}$ denotes the i -th spatial location and $~w_{iv}$ refers to the $iv$ -th entry of a spatial weight matrix and $w_{ii}=0$ for $~i=1,...,n$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] The spatial weight matrix defines which locations are considered to be adjacent.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] In spatiotemporal extensions, the conditional variance is modelled as a joint function of spatially lagged past squared observations and temporally lagged volatilities, allowing for both cross-sectional and serial dependence.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] These models have been applied in fields such as environmental statistics, regional economics, and financial econometrics, where shocks can propagate over space and time.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] Recent reviews summarise methodological developments, estimation techniques, and applications across disciplines.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-conditional-heteroskedasticity] In a different vein, the machine learning community has proposed the use of Gaussian process regression models to obtain a GARCH scheme.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] In time series analysis used in statistics and econometrics, **autoregressive integrated moving average** (**ARIMA**) and **seasonal ARIMA** (**SARIMA**) models are generalizations of the autoregressive moving average (ARMA) model to non-stationary series and periodic variation, respectively.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] All these models are fitted to time series in order to better understand it and predict future values.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The purpose of these generalizations is to fit the data as well as possible.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Specifically, ARMA assumes that the series is stationary, that is, its expected value is constant in time.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] If instead the series has a trend (but a constant variance/autocovariance), the trend is removed by "differencing", leaving a stationary series.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] This operation generalizes ARMA and corresponds to the "integrated" part of ARIMA.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Analogously, periodic variation is removed by "seasonal differencing".
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] As in ARMA, the "autoregressive" (AR) part of ARIMA indicates that the evolving variable of interest is regressed on its prior values.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The "moving average" (MA) part indicates that the regression error is a linear combination of error terms whose values occurred contemporaneously and at various times in the past.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The "integrated" (I) part indicates that the data values have been replaced with the difference between each value and the previous value.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] According to Wold's decomposition theorem the ARMA model is sufficient to describe a **regular** (a.k.a. purely nondeterministic) wide-sense stationary time series.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] This motivates to make such a non-stationary time series stationary, e.g., by using differencing, before using ARMA.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] If the time series contains a **predictable** sub-process (a.k.a. pure sine or complex-valued exponential process), the predictable component is treated as a non-zero-mean but periodic (i.e., seasonal) component in the ARIMA framework that it is eliminated by the seasonal differencing.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Seasonal ARIMA models are usually denoted by ARIMA(*p*, *d*, *q*)(*P*, *D*, *Q*)*m*, where the uppercase *P*, *D*, *Q* are the autoregressive, differencing, and moving average terms for the seasonal part of the ARIMA model, and *m* is the number of periods in each season.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] When two of the parameters are 0, the model may be referred to based on the non-zero parameter, dropping "AR", "I" or "MA" from the acronym.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] where L is the lag operator, the $\alpha _{i}$ are the parameters of the autoregressive part of the model, the $\theta _{i}$ are the parameters of the moving average part and the $\varepsilon _{t}$ are error terms.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The error terms $\varepsilon _{t}$ are generally assumed to be independent, identically distributed variables sampled from a normal distribution with zero mean.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] and so is special case of an ARMA(*p+d*, *q*) process having the autoregressive polynomial with *d* unit roots.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The above can be generalized as follows.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The explicit identification of the factorization of the autoregression polynomial into factors as above can be extended to other cases, firstly to apply to the moving average polynomial and secondly to include other special factors.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] For example, having a factor $(1-L^{s})$ in a model is one way of including a non-stationary seasonality of period *s* into the model; this factor has the effect of re-expressing the data as changes from *s* periods ago.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Another example is the factor $\left(1-{\sqrt {3}}L+L^{2}\right)$ , which includes a (non-stationary) seasonality of period 2.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The effect of the first type of factor is to allow each season's value to drift separately over time, whereas with the second type values for adjacent seasons move together.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] A stationary time series's properties do not change.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Specifically, for a wide-sense stationary time series, the mean and the variance/autocovariance are constant over time.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] **Differencing** in statistics is a transformation applied to a non-stationary time-series in order to make it trend stationary (i.e., stationary *in the mean sense*), by removing or subtracting the trend or non-constant mean.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] However, it does not affect the non-stationarity of the variance or autocovariance.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Likewise, *seasonal differencing* or *deseasonalization* is applied to a time-series to remove the seasonal component.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] From the perspective of signal processing, especially the Fourier spectral analysis theory, the trend is a low-frequency part in the spectrum of a series, while the season is a periodic-frequency part.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Therefore, differencing is a high-pass (that is, low-stop) filter and the seasonal-differencing is a comb filter to suppress respectively the low-frequency trend and the periodic-frequency season in the spectrum domain (rather than directly in the time domain).
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] To difference the data, we compute the difference between consecutive observations.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Seasonal differencing involves computing the difference between an observation and the corresponding observation in the previous season e.g a year.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The differenced data are then used for the estimation of an ARMA model.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Some well-known special cases arise naturally or are mathematically equivalent to other popular forecasting models.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The order *p* and *q* can be determined using the sample autocorrelation function (ACF), partial autocorrelation function (PACF), and/or extended autocorrelation function (EACF) method.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Other alternative methods include AIC, BIC, etc.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] To determine the order of a non-seasonal ARIMA model, a useful criterion is the Akaike information criterion (AIC).
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] where *L*is the likelihood of the data, *p*is the order of the autoregressive part and *q*is the order of the moving average part.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The *k* represents the intercept of the ARIMA model.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] For AIC, if *k* = 1 then there is an intercept in the ARIMA model (*c*≠ 0) and if *k*= 0 then there is no intercept in the ARIMA model (*c*= 0).
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The objective is to minimize the AIC, AICc or BIC values for a good model.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The lower the value of one of these criteria for a range of models being investigated, the better the model will suit the data.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The AIC and the BIC are used for two completely different purposes.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] While the AIC tries to approximate models towards the reality of the situation, the BIC attempts to find the perfect fit.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The BIC approach is often criticized as there never is a perfect fit to real-life complex data; however, it is still a useful method for selection as it penalizes models more heavily for having more parameters than the AIC would.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] AICc can only be used to compare ARIMA models with the same orders of differencing.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] For ARIMAs with different orders of differencing, RMSE can be used for model comparison.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The ARIMA model can be viewed as a "cascade" of two models.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Now forecasts can be made for the process $Y_{t}$ , using a generalization of the method of autoregressive forecasting.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The forecast intervals (confidence intervals for forecasts) for ARIMA models are based on assumptions that the residuals are uncorrelated and normally distributed.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] If either of these assumptions does not hold, then the forecast intervals may be incorrect.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] For this reason, researchers plot the ACF and histogram of the residuals to check the assumptions before producing forecast intervals.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] For $h=1$ , $v_{T+h\,\mid \,T}={\hat {\sigma }}^{2}$ for all ARIMA models regardless of parameters and orders.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] In general, forecast intervals from ARIMA models will increase as the forecast horizon increases.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] A number of variations on the ARIMA model are commonly employed.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] If multiple time series are used then the $X_{t}$ can be thought of as vectors and a VARIMA model may be appropriate.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Sometimes a seasonal effect is suspected in the model; in that case, it is generally considered better to use a SARIMA (seasonal ARIMA) model than to increase the order of the AR or MA parts of the model.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] If the time-series is suspected to exhibit long-range dependence, then the *d* parameter may be allowed to have non-integer values in an autoregressive fractionally integrated moving average model, which is also called a Fractional ARIMA (FARIMA or ARFIMA) model.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Various packages that apply methodology like Box–Jenkins parameter optimization are available to find the right parameters for the ARIMA model.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] In statistics, an **autoregressive** (**AR**) **model** is a modelled representation of a type of random process.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] It can be used to describe time-varying processes from many natural and artificial sources.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] The model specifies output variables that are dependent linearly on their own previous values on a stochastic basis.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] The model is in the form of a stochastic difference equation (or recurrence relation) which should not be confused with a differential equation.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] Another important extension is the time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) model, where the autoregressive coefficients are allowed to change over time to model evolving or non-stationary processes.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] TVAR models are widely applied in cases where the underlying dynamics of the system are not constant, such as in sensors time series modelling, climate science, economics and finance (as econometrics), signal processing, telecommunications, radar systems, and biological signals.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] Unlike the moving-average (MA) model, the autoregressive model is not always stationary; non-stationarity can arise either due to the presence of a unit root or due to time-varying model parameters, as in time-varying autoregressive models.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] Large language models are called autoregressive, but they are not a classical autoregressive model in this sense because they are not linear.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] The notation $AR(p)$ indicates an autoregressive model of order *p*.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] where $\varphi _{1},\ldots ,\varphi _{p}$ are the *parameters* of the model, and $\varepsilon _{t}$ is white noise.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] An autoregressive model can thus be viewed as the output of an all-pole infinite impulse response filter whose input is white noise.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] Some parameter constraints are necessary for the model to remain weak-sense stationary.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] For example, processes in the AR(1) model with $|\varphi _{1}|\geq 1$ are not stationary.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] More generally, for an AR(*p*) model to be weak-sense stationary, the roots of the polynomial $\Phi (z):=\textstyle 1-\sum _{i=1}^{p}\varphi _{i}z^{i}$ must lie outside the unit circle, i.e., each (complex) root $z_{i}$ must satisfy $|z_{i}|>1$ (see pages 89,92 ).
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] In an AR process, a one-time shock affects values of the evolving variable infinitely far into the future.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] A non-zero value for $\varepsilon _{t}$ at say time *t*=1 affects $X_{1}$ by the amount $\varepsilon _{1}$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] Then by the AR equation for $X_{2}$ in terms of $X_{1}$ , this affects $X_{2}$ by the amount $\varphi _{1}\varepsilon _{1}$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] Then by the AR equation for $X_{3}$ in terms of $X_{2}$ , this affects $X_{3}$ by the amount $\varphi _{1}^{2}\varepsilon _{1}$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] Continuing this process shows that the effect of $\varepsilon _{1}$ never ends, although if the process is stationary then the effect diminishes toward zero in the limit.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] Because each shock affects *X* values infinitely far into the future from when they occur, any given value *X**t* is affected by shocks occurring infinitely far into the past.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] When the polynomial division on the right side is carried out, the polynomial in the backshift operator applied to $\varepsilon _{t}$ has an infinite order—that is, an infinite number of lagged values of $\varepsilon _{t}$ appear on the right side of the equation.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] where *B* is the backshift operator, where $\varphi (\cdot )$ is the function defining the autoregression, and where $\varphi _{k}$ are the coefficients in the autoregression.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] The formula is valid only if all the roots have multiplicity 1.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] The autocorrelation function of an AR(*p*) process is a sum of decaying exponentials.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] The simplest AR process is AR(0), which has no dependence between the terms.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] Only the error/innovation/noise term contributes to the output of the process, so in the figure, AR(0) corresponds to white noise.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] For an AR(1) process with a positive $\varphi$ , only the previous term in the process and the noise term contribute to the output.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] If $\varphi$ is close to 0, then the process still looks like white noise, but as $\varphi$ approaches 1, the output gets a larger contribution from the previous term relative to the noise.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] This results in a "smoothing" or integration of the output, similar to a low pass filter.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] For an AR(2) process, the previous two terms and the noise term contribute to the output.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] If both $\varphi _{1}$ and $\varphi _{2}$ are positive, the output will resemble a low pass filter, with the high frequency part of the noise decreased.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] If $\varphi _{1}$ is positive while $\varphi _{2}$ is negative, then the process favors changes in sign between terms of the process.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] This can be linked to edge detection or detection of change in direction.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] An AR(1) process is given by: $X_{t}=\varphi X_{t-1}+\varepsilon _{t}\,$ where $\varepsilon _{t}$ is a white noise process with zero mean and constant variance $\sigma _{\varepsilon }^{2}$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] (Note: The subscript on $\varphi _{1}$ has been dropped.) The process is weak-sense stationary if $|\varphi |<1$ since it is obtained as the output of a stable filter whose input is white noise.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] where $\sigma _{\varepsilon }$ is the standard deviation of $\varepsilon _{t}$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] and then by noticing that the quantity above is a stable fixed point of this relation.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] It can be seen that the autocovariance function decays with a decay time (also called time constant) of $\tau =1/(1-\varphi )$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] The spectral density function is the Fourier transform of the autocovariance function.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] This expression is periodic due to the discrete nature of the $X_{j}$ , which is manifested as the cosine term in the denominator.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] where $\gamma =1/\tau$ is the angular frequency associated with the decay time $\tau$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] An alternative expression for $X_{t}$ can be derived by first substituting $\varphi X_{t-2}+\varepsilon _{t-1}$ for $X_{t-1}$ in the defining equation.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] It is seen that $X_{t}$ is white noise convolved with the $\varphi ^{k}$ kernel plus the constant mean.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] If the white noise $\varepsilon _{t}$ is a Gaussian process then $X_{t}$ is also a Gaussian process.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] In other cases, the central limit theorem indicates that $X_{t}$ will be approximately normally distributed when $\varphi$ is close to one.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] For $\varepsilon _{t}=0$ , the process $X_{t}=\varphi X_{t-1}$ will be a geometric progression (*exponential* growth or decay).
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] In this case, the solution can be found analytically: $X_{t}=a\varphi ^{t}$ whereby a is an unknown constant (initial condition).
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] The AR(1) model is the discrete-time analogy of the continuous Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] It is therefore sometimes useful to understand the properties of the AR(1) model cast in an equivalent form.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] The partial autocorrelation of an AR(p) process equals zero at lags larger than *p*, so the appropriate maximum lag *p* is the one after which the partial autocorrelations are all zero.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] There are many ways to estimate the coefficients, such as the ordinary least squares procedure or method of moments (through Yule–Walker equations).
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] It is based on parameters $\varphi _{i}$ where *i* = 1, ..., *p*.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] There is a direct correspondence between these parameters and the covariance function of the process, and this correspondence can be inverted to determine the parameters from the autocorrelation function (which is itself obtained from the covariances).
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] This is done using the Yule–Walker equations.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] The Yule–Walker equations, named for Udny Yule and Gilbert Walker, are the following set of equations.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] Here $\gamma _{m}$ is the autocovariance function of Xt, $\sigma _{\varepsilon }$ is the standard deviation of the input noise process, and $\delta _{m,0}$ is the Kronecker delta function.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] An alternative formulation is in terms of the autocorrelation function.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] The AR parameters are determined by the first *p*+1 elements $\rho (\tau )$ of the autocorrelation function.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] The above equations (the Yule–Walker equations) provide several routes to estimating the parameters of an AR(*p*) model, by replacing the theoretical covariances with estimated values.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] but the reasoning behind this applies to the use of any set of estimated AR parameters.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] Compared to the estimation scheme using only the forward prediction equations, different estimates of the autocovariances are produced, and the estimates have different stability properties.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] Other possible approaches to estimation include maximum likelihood estimation.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] Substantial differences in the results of these approaches can occur if the observed series is short, or if the process is close to non-stationarity.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] The terms involving square roots are all real in the case of complex poles since they exist only when $\varphi _{2}<0$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] The process is non-stationary when the poles are on or outside the unit circle, or equivalently when the characteristic roots are on or inside the unit circle.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] The process is stable when the poles are strictly within the unit circle (roots strictly outside the unit circle), or equivalently when the coefficients are in the triangle $-1\leq \varphi _{2}\leq 1-|\varphi _{1}|$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] The impulse response of a system is the change in an evolving variable in response to a change in the value of a shock term *k* periods earlier, as a function of *k*.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] Since the AR model is a special case of the vector autoregressive model, the computation of the impulse response in vector autoregression#impulse response applies here.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] have been estimated, the autoregression can be used to forecast an arbitrary number of periods into the future.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] The output of the autoregressive equation is the forecast for the first unobserved period.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] Then for future periods the same procedure is used, each time using one more forecast value on the right side of the predictive equation until, after *p* predictions, all *p* right-side values are predicted values from preceding steps.
[src:time-series-econometrics/autoregressive-model] Each of the last three can be quantified and combined to give a confidence interval for the *n*-step-ahead predictions; the confidence interval will become wider as *n* increases because of the use of an increasing number of estimated values for the right-side variables.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] In econometrics, **cointegration** is a statistical property that describes a long-run equilibrium relationship among two or more time series variables, even if the individual series are non-stationary (i.e., they contain stochastic trends).
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] In such cases, the variables may drift in the short run, but their linear combination is stationary, implying that they move together over time and remain bound by a stable equilibrium.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] More formally, if several time series are individually integrated of order *d* (meaning they require *d* differences to become stationary) but a linear combination of them is integrated of a lower order, then those time series are said to be cointegrated.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] That is, if (*X*,*Y*,*Z*) are each integrated of order *d*, and there exist coefficients *a*,*b*,*c* such that *aX* + *bY* + *cZ* is integrated of order less than d, then *X*, *Y*, and *Z* are cointegrated.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] Cointegration is a crucial concept in time series analysis, particularly when dealing with variables that exhibit trends, such as macroeconomic data.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] In an influential paper, Charles Nelson and Charles Plosser (1982) provided statistical evidence that many US macroeconomic time series (like GNP, wages, employment, etc.) have stochastic trends.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] If two or more series are individually integrated (in the time series sense) but some linear combination of them has a lower order of integration, then the series are said to be cointegrated.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] A common example is where the individual series are first-order integrated (⁠ $I(1)$ ⁠) but some (cointegrating) vector of coefficients exists to form a stationary linear combination of them.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] The first to introduce and analyse the concept of spurious—or nonsense—regression was Udny Yule in 1926.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] Granger's 1987 paper with Robert Engle formalized the cointegrating vector approach, and coined the term.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] For integrated ⁠ $I(1)$ ⁠ processes, Granger and Newbold showed that de-trending does not work to eliminate the problem of spurious correlation, and that the superior alternative is to check for co-integration.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] Two series with ⁠ $I(1)$ ⁠ trends can be co-integrated only if there is a genuine relationship between the two.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] Thus the standard current methodology for time series regressions is to check all-time series involved for integration.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] If there are ⁠ $I(1)$ ⁠ series on both sides of the regression relationship, then it is possible for regressions to give misleading results.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] The possible presence of cointegration must be taken into account when choosing a technique to test hypotheses concerning the relationship between two variables having unit roots (i.e. integrated of at least order one).
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] The usual procedure for testing hypotheses concerning the relationship between non-stationary variables was to run ordinary least squares (OLS) regressions on data which had been differenced.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] This method is biased if the non-stationary variables are cointegrated.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] For example, regressing the consumption series for any country (e.g.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] Fiji) against the GNP for a randomly selected dissimilar country (e.g.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] Afghanistan) might give a high R-squared relationship (suggesting high explanatory power on Fiji's consumption from Afghanistan's GNP).
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] This is called spurious regression: two integrated ⁠ $I(1)$ ⁠ series which are not directly causally related may nonetheless show a significant correlation.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] If $x_{t}$ and $y_{t}$ both have order of integration *d*=1 and are cointegrated, then a linear combination of them must be stationary for some value of $\beta$ and $u_{t}$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] If $\beta$ is known, we can test $u_{t}$ for stationarity with an augmented Dickey–Fuller test or Phillips–Perron test.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] If $\beta$ is unknown, we must first estimate it.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] This is typically done by using ordinary least squares (by regressing $y_{t}$ on $x_{t}$ and an intercept).
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] Then, we can run an ADF test on $u_{t}$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] However, when $\beta$ is estimated, the critical values of this ADF test are non-standard, and increase in absolute value as more regressors are included.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] If the variables are found to be cointegrated, a second-stage regression is conducted.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] This is a regression of $\Delta y_{t}$ on the lagged regressors, $\Delta x_{t}$ and the lagged residuals from the first stage, ${\hat {u}}_{t-1}$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] The Johansen test is a test for cointegration that allows for more than one cointegrating relationship, unlike the Engle–Granger method, but this test is subject to asymptotic properties, i.e. large samples.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] If the sample size is too small then the results will not be reliable and one should use Auto Regressive Distributed Lags (ARDL).
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] Phillips and Sam Ouliaris (1990) show that residual-based unit root tests applied to the estimated cointegrating residuals do not have the usual Dickey–Fuller distributions under the null hypothesis of no-cointegration.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] Because of the spurious regression phenomenon under the null hypothesis, the distribution of these tests have asymptotic distributions that depend on (1) the number of deterministic trend terms and (2) the number of variables with which co-integration is being tested.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] These distributions are known as Phillips–Ouliaris distributions and critical values have been tabulated.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] In finite samples, a superior alternative to the use of these asymptotic critical value is to generate critical values from simulations.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] In practice, cointegration is often used for two ⁠ $I(1)$ ⁠ series, but it is more generally applicable and can be used for variables integrated of higher order (to detect correlated accelerations or other second-difference effects).
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] **Multicointegration** extends the cointegration technique beyond two variables, and occasionally to variables integrated at different orders.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] Tests for cointegration assume that the cointegrating vector is constant during the period of study.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] In reality, it is possible that the long-run relationship between the underlying variables change (shifts in the cointegrating vector can occur).
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] The reason for this might be technological progress, economic crises, changes in the people's preferences and behaviour accordingly, policy or regime alteration, and organizational or institutional developments.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] This is especially likely to be the case if the sample period is long.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] To take this issue into account, tests have been introduced for cointegration with one unknown structural break, and tests for cointegration with two unknown breaks are also available.
[src:time-series-econometrics/cointegration] Several Bayesian methods have been proposed to compute the posterior distribution of the number of cointegrating relationships and the cointegrating linear combinations.
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] In statistics, the **Dickey–Fuller test** tests the null hypothesis that a unit root is present in an autoregressive (AR) time series model.
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] The alternative hypothesis is different depending on which version of the test is used, but is usually stationarity or trend-stationarity.
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] The test is named after the statisticians David Dickey and Wayne Fuller, who developed it in 1979.
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] where $y_{t}$ is the variable of interest, t is the time index, $\rho$ is a coefficient, and $u_{t}$ is the error term (assumed to be white noise).
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] The model would be non-stationary in this case.
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] where $\Delta$ is the first difference operator and $\delta \equiv \rho -1$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] This model can be estimated, and testing for a unit root is equivalent to testing $\delta =0$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] Since the test is done over the residual term rather than raw data, it is not possible to use standard t-distribution to provide critical values.
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] Therefore, this statistic t has a specific distribution simply known as the Dickey–Fuller table.
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] Each version of the test has its own critical value which depends on the size of the sample.
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] In each case, the null hypothesis is that there is a unit root, $\delta =0$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] The tests have low statistical power in that they often cannot distinguish between true unit-root processes ( $\delta =0$ ) and near unit-root processes ( $\delta$ is close to zero).
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] This is called the "near observation equivalence" problem.
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] The intuition behind the test is as follows.
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] If the series y is stationary (or trend-stationary), then it has a tendency to return to a constant (or deterministically trending) mean.
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] Therefore, large values will tend to be followed by smaller values (negative changes), and small values by larger values (positive changes).
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] Accordingly, the level of the series will be a significant predictor of next period's change, and will have a negative coefficient.
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] If, on the other hand, the series is integrated, then positive changes and negative changes will occur with probabilities that do not depend on the current level of the series; in a random walk, where you are now does not affect which way you will go next.
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] with a deterministic trend coming from $a_{0}t$ and a stochastic intercept term coming from $y_{0}+\sum _{i=1}^{t}u_{i}$ , resulting in what is referred to as a *stochastic trend*.
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] There is also an extension of the Dickey–Fuller (DF) test called the augmented Dickey–Fuller test (ADF), which removes all the structural effects (autocorrelation) in the time series and then tests using the same procedure.
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] Which of the three main versions of the test should be used is not a minor issue.
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] The decision is important for the size of the unit root test (the probability of rejecting the null hypothesis of a unit root when there is one) and the power of the unit root test (the probability of rejecting the null hypothesis of a unit root when there is not one).
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] Inappropriate exclusion of the intercept or deterministic time trend term leads to bias in the coefficient estimate for *δ*, leading to the actual size for the unit root test not matching the reported one.
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] If the time trend term is inappropriately excluded with the $a_{0}$ term estimated, then the power of the unit root test can be substantially reduced as a trend may be captured through the random walk with drift model.
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] On the other hand, inappropriate inclusion of the intercept or time trend term reduces the power of the unit root test, and sometimes that reduced power can be substantial.
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] Use of prior knowledge about whether the intercept and deterministic time trend should be included is of course ideal but not always possible.
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] When such prior knowledge is unavailable, various testing strategies (series of ordered tests) have been suggested, e.g. by Dolado, Jenkinson, and Sosvilla-Rivero (1990) and by Enders (2004), often with the ADF extension to remove autocorrelation.
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] Elder and Kennedy (2001) present a simple testing strategy that avoids double and triple testing for the unit root that can occur with other testing strategies, and discuss how to use prior knowledge about the existence or not of long-run growth (or shrinkage) in *y*.
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] Hacker and Hatemi-J (2010) provide simulation results on these matters, including simulations covering the Enders (2004) and Elder and Kennedy (2001) unit-root testing strategies.
[src:time-series-econometrics/dickey-fuller-test] Simulation results are presented in Hacker (2010) which indicate that using an information criterion such as the Schwarz information criterion may be useful in determining unit root and trend status within a Dickey–Fuller framework.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] The **Granger causality test** is a statistical hypothesis test for determining whether one time series is useful in forecasting another, first proposed in 1969.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] Ordinarily, regressions reflect "mere" correlations, but Clive Granger argued that causality in economics could be tested for by measuring the ability to predict the future values of a time series using prior values of another time series.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] Since the question of "true causality" is deeply philosophical, and because of the post hoc ergo propter hoc fallacy of assuming that one thing preceding another can be used as a proof of causation, econometricians assert that the Granger test finds only "predictive causality".
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] Using the term "causality" alone is a misnomer, as Granger-causality is better described as "precedence", or, as Granger himself later claimed in 1977, "temporally related".
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] A time series *X* is said to Granger-cause *Y* if it can be shown, usually through a series of t-tests and F-tests on lagged values of *X* (and with lagged values of *Y* also included), that those *X* values provide statistically significant information about future values of *Y*.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] Granger also stressed that some studies using "Granger causality" testing in areas outside economics reached "ridiculous" conclusions.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] "Of course, many ridiculous papers appeared", he said in his Nobel lecture.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] However, it remains a popular method for causality analysis in time series due to its computational simplicity.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] The original definition of Granger causality does not account for latent confounding effects and does not capture instantaneous and non-linear causal relationships, though several extensions have been proposed to address these issues.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] We say that a variable *X* that evolves over time *Granger-causes* another evolving variable *Y* if predictions of the value of *Y* based on its own past values *and* on the past values of *X* are better than predictions of *Y* based only on *Y'*s own past values.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] The cause has *unique* information about the future values of its effect.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] where $\mathbb {P}$ refers to probability, A is an arbitrary non-empty set, and ${\mathcal {I}}(t)$ and ${\mathcal {I}}_{-X}(t)$ respectively denote the information available as of time t in the entire universe, and that in the modified universe in which X is excluded.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] If the above hypothesis is accepted, we say that X Granger-causes Y .
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] If a time series is a stationary process, the test is performed using the level values of two (or more) variables.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] If the variables are non-stationary, then the test is done using first (or higher) differences.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] The number of lags to be included is usually chosen using an information criterion, such as the Akaike information criterion or the Schwarz information criterion.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] Any particular lagged value of one of the variables is retained in the regression if (1) it is significant according to a t-test, and (2) it and the other lagged values of the variable jointly add explanatory power to the model according to an F-test.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] Then the null hypothesis of no Granger causality is not rejected if and only if no lagged values of an explanatory variable have been retained in the regression.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] In practice it may be found that neither variable Granger-causes the other, or that each of the two variables Granger-causes the other.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] Let *y* and *x* be stationary time series.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] One retains in this regression all lagged values of *x* that are individually significant according to their t-statistics, provided that collectively they add explanatory power to the regression according to an F-test (whose null hypothesis is no explanatory power jointly added by the *x'*s).
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] In the notation of the above augmented regression, *p* is the shortest, and *q* is the longest, lag length for which the lagged value of *x* is significant.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] The null hypothesis that *x* does not Granger-cause *y* is not rejected if and only if no lagged values of *x* are retained in the regression.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] Multivariate Granger causality analysis is usually performed by fitting a vector autoregressive model (VAR) to the time series.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] In particular, let $X(t)\in \mathbb {R} ^{d\times 1}$ for $t=1,\ldots ,T$ be a d -dimensional multivariate time series.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] where $\varepsilon (t)$ is a white Gaussian random vector, and $A_{\tau }$ is a matrix for every $\tau$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] A time series $X_{i}$ is called a Granger cause of another time series $X_{j}$ , if at least one of the elements $A_{\tau }(j,i)$ for $\tau =1,\ldots ,L$ is significantly larger than zero (in absolute value).
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] The above linear methods are appropriate for testing Granger causality in the mean.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] However they are not able to detect Granger causality in higher moments, e.g., in the variance.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] Non-parametric tests for Granger causality are designed to address this problem.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] The definition of Granger causality in these tests is general and does not involve any modelling assumptions, such as a linear autoregressive model.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] The non-parametric tests for Granger causality can be used as diagnostic tools to build better parametric models including higher order moments and/or non-linearity.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] As its name implies, Granger causality is not necessarily true causality.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] If both *X* and *Y* are driven by a common third process with different lags, one might still fail to reject the alternative hypothesis of Granger causality.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] Yet, manipulation of one of the variables would not change the other.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] Indeed, the Granger-causality tests are designed to handle pairs of variables, and may produce misleading results when the true relationship involves three or more variables.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] Having said this, it has been argued that given a probabilistic view of causation, Granger causality can be considered true causality in that sense, especially when Reichenbach's "screening off" notion of probabilistic causation is taken into account.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] Other possible sources of misguiding test results are: (1) not frequent enough or too frequent sampling, (2) nonlinear causal relationship, (3) time series nonstationarity and nonlinearity and (4) existence of rational expectations.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] A similar test involving more variables can be applied with vector autoregression.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] A method for Granger causality has been developed that is not sensitive to deviations from the assumption that the error term is normally distributed.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] This method is especially useful in financial economics, since many financial variables are non-normally distributed.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] Recently, asymmetric causality testing has been suggested in the literature in order to separate the causal impact of positive changes from the negative ones.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] An extension of Granger (non-)causality testing to panel data is also available.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] A modified Granger causality test based on the GARCH (generalized auto-regressive conditional heteroscedasticity) type of integer-valued time series models is available in many areas.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] The extension of Granger causality to incorporate its dynamic, time-varying nature allows for a more nuanced understanding of how causal relationships in time-series data evolve over time.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] The methodology uses recursive techniques such as the Forward Expanding (FE), Rolling (RO), and Recursive Evolving (RE) windows to overcome the limitations of traditional Granger causality tests and understand changes in causal relationships across different periods.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] A central aspect of this methodology is the 'tvgc' command in Stata.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] Empirical applications, such as data involving transaction fees and economic sub-systems on Ethereum, highlight the dynamic nature of economic relationships over time.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] A long-held belief about neural function maintained that different areas of the brain were task specific; that the structural connectivity local to a certain area somehow dictated the function of that piece.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] Collecting work that has been performed over many years, there has been a move to a different, network-centric approach to describing information flow in the brain.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] Explanation of function is beginning to include the concept of networks existing at different levels and throughout different locations in the brain.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] The behavior of these networks can be described by non-deterministic processes that are evolving through time.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] That is to say that given the same input stimulus, you will not get the same output from the network.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] The dynamics of these networks are governed by probabilities so we treat them as stochastic (random) processes so that we can capture these kinds of dynamics between different areas of the brain.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] Recently Granger causality has been applied to address some of these issues.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] Put plainly, one examines how to best predict the future of a neuron: using either the entire ensemble or the entire ensemble except a certain target neuron.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] If the prediction is made worse by excluding the target neuron, then we say it has a "g-causal" relationship with the current neuron.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] Previous Granger-causality methods could only operate on continuous-valued data so the analysis of neural spike train recordings involved transformations that ultimately altered the stochastic properties of the data, indirectly altering the validity of the conclusions that could be drawn from it.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] In 2011, however, a new general-purpose Granger-causality framework was proposed that could directly operate on any modality, including neural-spike trains.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] Neural spike train data can be modeled as a point-process.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] A temporal point process is a stochastic time-series of binary events that occurs in continuous time.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] It can only take on two values at each point in time, indicating whether or not an event has actually occurred.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] This type of binary-valued representation of information suits the activity of neural populations because a single neuron's action potential has a typical waveform.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] In this way, what carries the actual information being output from a neuron is the occurrence of a "spike", as well as the time between successive spikes.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] Using this approach one could abstract the flow of information in a neural-network to be simply the spiking times for each neuron through an observation period.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] One of the simplest types of neural-spiking models is the Poisson process.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] This however, is limited in that it is memory-less.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] It does not account for any spiking history when calculating the current probability of firing.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] Neurons, however, exhibit a fundamental (biophysical) history dependence by way of its relative and absolute refractory periods.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] To address this, a conditional intensity function is used to represent the probability of a neuron spiking, conditioned on its own history.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] The conditional intensity function expresses the instantaneous firing probability and implicitly defines a complete probability model for the point process.
[src:time-series-econometrics/granger-causality] So if this unit time is taken small enough to ensure that only one spike could occur in that time window, then our conditional intensity function completely specifies the probability that a given neuron will fire in a certain time.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] In probability theory and statistics, a **unit root** is a property of certain stochastic processes (such as a random walk) that can create challenges for statistical inference in time series models.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] A linear stochastic process contains a unit root if 1 is a solution to its characteristic equation.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] Processes with a unit root are non-stationary, because they do not necessarily exhibit a deterministic trend.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] If the other roots of the characteristic equation lie inside the unit circle—that is, have a modulus (absolute value) less than one—then the first difference of the process will be stationary; otherwise, the process will need to be differenced multiple times to become stationary.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] If there are *d* unit roots, the process will have to be differenced *d* times in order to make it stationary.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] Unit root processes may sometimes be confused with trend-stationary processes; while they share many properties, they are different in many aspects.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] It is possible for a time series to be non-stationary, yet have no unit root and be trend-stationary.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] If a root of the process's characteristic equation is larger than 1, then it is called an **explosive process**, even though such processes are sometimes inaccurately called unit roots processes.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] The presence of a unit root can be tested using a unit root test.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] Here, $(\varepsilon _{t},t=0,1,2,\ldots ,)$ is a serially uncorrelated, zero-mean stochastic process with constant variance $\sigma ^{2}$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] then the stochastic process has a **unit root** or, alternatively, is integrated of order one, denoted $I(1)$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] If *m* = 1 is a root of multiplicity *r*, then the stochastic process is integrated of order *r*, denoted *I*(*r*).
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] In this example, the characteristic equation is $m-a_{1}=0$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] If the process has a unit root, then it is a non-stationary time series.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] That is, the moments of the stochastic process depend on t .
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] The variance of the series is diverging to infinity with *t*.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] The finite sample properties of regression models with first order ARMA errors, including unit roots, have been analyzed.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] Often, ordinary least squares (OLS) is used to estimate the slope coefficients of the autoregressive model.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] Use of OLS relies on the stochastic process being stationary.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] When the stochastic process is non-stationary, the use of OLS can produce invalid estimates.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] Granger and Newbold called such estimates 'spurious regression' results: high R2 values and high t-ratios yielding results with no real (in their context, economic) meaning.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] To estimate the slope coefficients, one should first conduct a unit root test, whose null hypothesis is that a unit root is present.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] If that hypothesis is rejected, one can use OLS.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] However, if the presence of a unit root is not rejected, then one should apply the difference operator to the series.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] If another unit root test shows the differenced time series to be stationary, OLS can then be applied to this series to estimate the slope coefficients.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] OLS can be used to estimate the slope coefficient, $\lambda _{1}$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] If the process has multiple unit roots, the difference operator can be applied multiple times.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] Economists debate whether various economic statistics, especially output, have a unit root or are trend-stationary.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] where *c* is a constant term referred to as the "drift" term, and $e_{t}$ is white noise.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] Any non-zero value of the noise term, occurring for only one period, will permanently affect the value of $y_{t}$ as shown in the graph, so deviations from the line $y_{t}=a+ct$ are non-stationary; there is no reversion to any trend line.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] where *k* is the slope of the trend and $u_{t}$ is noise (white noise in the simplest case; more generally, noise following its own stationary autoregressive process).
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] Here any transient noise will not alter the long-run tendency for $y_{t}$ to be on the trend line, as also shown in the graph.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] This process is said to be trend-stationary because deviations from the trend line are stationary.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] The issue is particularly popular in the literature on business cycles.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] Research on the subject began with Nelson and Plosser whose paper on GNP and other output aggregates failed to reject the unit root hypothesis for these series.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] Since then, a debate—entwined with technical disputes on statistical methods—has ensued.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] Some economists argue that GDP has a unit root or structural break, implying that economic downturns result in permanently lower GDP levels in the long run.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] Other economists argue that GDP is trend-stationary: That is, when GDP dips below trend during a downturn it later returns to the level implied by the trend so that there is no permanent decrease in output.
[src:time-series-econometrics/unit-root] While the literature on the unit root hypothesis may consist of arcane debate on statistical methods, the hypothesis carries significant practical implications for economic forecasts and policies.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] Like the autoregressive model, each variable has an equation modelling its evolution over time.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] This equation includes the variable's lagged (past) values, the lagged values of the other variables in the model, and an error term.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] VAR models do not require as much knowledge about the forces influencing a variable as do structural models with simultaneous equations.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] The only prior knowledge required is a list of variables which can be hypothesized to affect each other over time.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] A VAR model describes the evolution of a set of *k* variables, called *endogenous variables*, over time.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] Each period of time is numbered, *t* = 1, ..., *T*.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] The variables are collected in a vector, *yt*, which is of length *k.* (Equivalently, this vector might be described as a (*k* × 1)-matrix.) The vector is modelled as a linear function of its previous value.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] The vector's components are referred to as *y**i*,*t*, meaning the observation at time *t* of the *i* th variable.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] For example, if the first variable in the model measures the price of wheat over time, then *y*1,1998 would indicate the price of wheat in the year 1998.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] VAR models are characterized by their *order*, which refers to the number of earlier time periods the model will use.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] Continuing the above example, a 5th-order VAR would model each year's wheat price as a linear combination of the last five years of wheat prices.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] A *lag* is the value of a variable in a previous time period.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] So in general a *p*th-order VAR refers to a VAR model which includes lags for the last *p* time periods.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] A *p*th-order VAR is denoted "VAR(*p*)" and sometimes called "a VAR with *p* lags".
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] The variables of the form *y**t*−i indicate that variable's value *i* time periods earlier and are called the "i*th* lag" of *y*t.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] The variable *c* is a *k*-vector of constants serving as the intercept of the model.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] *Ai* is a time-invariant (*k* × *k*)-matrix and *e**t* is a *k*-vector of error terms.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] The contemporaneous covariance matrix of error terms is a *k* × *k* positive-semidefinite matrix denoted Ω.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] In particular, there is no serial correlation in individual error terms.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] The process of choosing the maximum lag *p* in the VAR model requires special attention because inference is dependent on correctness of the selected lag order.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] Note that all variables have to be of the same order of integration.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] Each variable in the model has one equation.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] The current (time *t*) observation of each variable depends on its own lagged values as well as on the lagged values of each other variable in the VAR.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] A VAR with *p* lags can always be equivalently rewritten as a VAR with only one lag by appropriately redefining the dependent variable.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] The transformation amounts to stacking the lags of the VAR(*p*) variable in the new VAR(1) dependent variable and appending identities to complete the precise number of equations.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] The equivalent VAR(1) form is more convenient for analytical derivations and allows more compact statements.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] where *c*0 is a *k* × 1 vector of constants, *Bi* is a *k* × *k* matrix (for every *i* = 0, ..., *p*) and *ε**t* is a *k* × 1 vector of error terms.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] The main diagonal terms of the *B*0 matrix (the coefficients on the *i*th variable in the *i*th equation) are scaled to 1.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] The error terms ε*t* (***structural shocks***) satisfy the conditions (1) - (3) in the definition above, with the particularity that all the elements in the off diagonal of the covariance matrix $\mathrm {E} (\epsilon _{t}\epsilon _{t}')=\Sigma$ are zero.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] That is, the structural shocks are uncorrelated.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] that is, the variances of the structural shocks are denoted $\mathrm {var} (\epsilon _{i})=\sigma _{i}^{2}$ (*i* = 1, 2) and the covariance is $\mathrm {cov} (\epsilon _{1},\epsilon _{2})=0$ .
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] Note that *y*2,*t* can have a contemporaneous effect on *y1,t* if *B*0;1,2 is not zero.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] This is different from the case when *B*0 is the identity matrix (all off-diagonal elements are zero — the case in the initial definition), when *y*2,*t* can impact directly *y*1,*t*+1 and subsequent future values, but not *y*1,*t*.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] Because of the parameter identification problem, ordinary least squares estimation of the structural VAR would yield inconsistent parameter estimates.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] This problem can be overcome by rewriting the VAR in reduced form.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] From an economic point of view, if the joint dynamics of a set of variables can be represented by a VAR model, then the structural form is a depiction of the underlying, "structural", economic relationships.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] , which implies zero correlation between error terms as a desired property.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] This is helpful for separating out the effects of economically unrelated influences in the VAR.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] ); therefore one would expect these factors to be statistically independent.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] This is a desirable feature especially when using low frequency data.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] the day the decision is announced, but one could find an effect in that quarter's data.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] Note that in the reduced form all right hand side variables are predetermined at time *t*.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] As there are no time *t* endogenous variables on the right hand side, no variable has a *direct* contemporaneous effect on other variables in the model.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] However, the error terms in the reduced VAR are composites of the structural shocks *e**t* = *B*0−1*ε**t*.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] Thus, the occurrence of one structural shock *εi,t* can potentially lead to the occurrence of shocks in all error terms *ej,t*, thus creating contemporaneous movement in all endogenous variables.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] can have non-zero off-diagonal elements, thus allowing non-zero correlation between error terms.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] where $\otimes$ denotes the Kronecker product and Vec the vectorization of the indicated matrix.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] This estimator is consistent and asymptotically efficient.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] It is furthermore equal to the conditional maximum likelihood estimator.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] As in the standard case, the maximum likelihood estimator (MLE) of the covariance matrix differs from the ordinary least squares (OLS) estimator.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] Vector autoregression models often involve the estimation of many parameters.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] This can hurt the accuracy of the parameter estimates and hence of the forecasts given by the model.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] for evolving (state) vector y and vector e of shocks.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] An estimated VAR model can be used for forecasting, and the quality of the forecasts can be judged, in ways that are completely analogous to the methods used in univariate autoregressive modelling.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] Christopher Sims has advocated VAR models, criticizing the claims and performance of earlier modeling in macroeconomic econometrics.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] He recommended VAR models, which had previously appeared in time series statistics and in system identification, a statistical specialty in control theory.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] Sims advocated VAR models as providing a theory-free method to estimate economic relationships, thus being an alternative to the "incredible identification restrictions" in structural models.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] VAR models are also increasingly used in health research for automatic analyses of diary data or sensor data.
[src:time-series-econometrics/vector-autoregression] Caraka found that the artificial neural network can improve its performance with the addition of the hybrid vector autoregression component.
